questions.description:
Specificity is the tie-breaker. Pick the resulting color.

```css
#header .nav a           { color: blue; }
header nav a.link.active { color: red;  }
```

`<h1 id="title">` matches both rules. Pick the winning color.

```css
@layer base, components;

@layer components { h1     { color: green; } }
@layer base      { #title { color: red;   } }
```

questions.explanation:
This is the headline surprise of cascade layers: **layer order is compared before specificity**. The cascade sorts candidates by origin & importance, then by *cascade layer*, and only then by specificity and source order. A declaration in a winning layer beats a more specific selector in a losing layer.

The statement `@layer base, components;` fixes the order — `base` first, `components` second — so `components` is the **higher-priority** layer. (Re-opening `@layer base {…}` later in the file does *not* change the order; only the first mention of a layer name sets its position.) The `h1` rule in `components` therefore wins over the `#title` rule in `base`, even though `#title` is far more specific **and** appears later in the source. The heading is **green**.

```css
@layer base, components;            /* precedence: base < components */
@layer components { h1     { color: green; } } /* (0,0,1), later layer → wins */
@layer base      { #title { color: red;   } } /* (1,0,0), earlier layer → loses */
```

This is the whole point of layers: drop high-specificity third-party CSS into an early layer, then override it with simple selectors in a later one.

questions.description:
Both declarations are `!important`. Pick the resulting color.

```css
@layer base, theme;

@layer base  { button { color: red   !important; } }
@layer theme { button { color: green !important; } }
```

questions.explanation:
For **normal** declarations, later layers win. For **`!important`** declarations, the layer order is **reversed** — earlier layers win. This is the mechanism that lets a base/reset layer assert non-negotiable rules that later layers cannot override, even with their own `!important`.

With `@layer base, theme;`, `theme` normally beats `base`. But both declarations here are `!important`, so the order flips and **`base` wins** → the button is **red**.

```css
@layer base, theme;
@layer base  { button { color: red   !important; } } /* important + earliest layer → wins */
@layer theme { button { color: green !important; } }
```

Mnemonic: `!important` turns the layer stack upside down.

questions.description:
Both are plain `a { color }` with equal specificity. Pick the winning color.

```css
a { color: red; }

@layer base { a { color: green; } }
```
